Part 1 - Introduction¶

Lending Club connects people who need money (borrowers) with people who have money (investors). Here we will use Python with some packages like Pandas, Matplotlib and seaborn to analyze a dataset that was collected on lending.com over 2007-2010. The dataset contains data on more than 9000 borrowers and borrowers' features like income, FICO, interest rate, etc. We will analyze this data to get insights on the main difference between fully paid borrowers and not fully paid borrowers. These insights might also be used by people in landing.com to better predict whether the borrower will pay in full or not.

Goals of the analysis¶

We want to answer questions like:

  • What are the main differences between not fully paid and fully paid borrowers?
  • What are the main purposes of the borrowers that use lending.com? How does interest rate differ between each purpose? How do purposes correlate with other features?
  • Do fully paid borrowers tend to have lower revolving balance than not fully paid borrwers? What about revolving utilization rate?
  • How do income and FICO impact borrower's interest rate?
  • Given the same FICO socre, do fully paid borrowers tend to have lower interest rate? What about different credit policies?
  • Do fully paid borrowers have less public record and tend to pay back on time? How will these behaviors impact interest rate?

First let's load the necessary packages and data.

Here are what the columns represent:

  • credit.policy: 1 if the customer meets the credit underwriting criteria of LendingClub.com, and 0 otherwise.
  • purpose: The purpose of the loan (takes values "credit_card", "debt_consolidation", "educational", "major_purchase", "small_business", and "all_other").
  • int.rate: The interest rate of the loan, as a proportion (a rate of 11% would be stored as 0.11). Borrowers judged by LendingClub.com to be more risky are assigned higher interest rates.
  • installment: The monthly installments owed by the borrower if the loan is funded.
  • log.annual.inc: The natural log of the self-reported annual income of the borrower.
  • dti: The debt-to-income ratio of the borrower (amount of debt divided by annual income).
  • fico: The FICO credit score of the borrower.
  • days.with.cr.line: The number of days the borrower has had a credit line.
  • revol.bal: The borrower's revolving balance (amount unpaid at the end of the credit card billing cycle).
  • revol.util: The borrower's revolving line utilization rate (the amount of the credit line used relative to total credit available).
  • inq.last.6mths: The borrower's number of inquiries by creditors in the last 6 months.
  • delinq.2yrs: The number of times the borrower had been 30+ days past due on a payment in the past 2 years.
  • pub.rec: The borrower's number of derogatory public records (bankruptcy filings, tax liens, or judgments).

In conclusion, for categorical variable, purposes, we found that:

  • Debt consolidation and credit card are the most popular purposes for both kinds of borrowers
  • For borrowers that paid in full, home improvement is another popular purpose. For borrowers that didn't pay in full, small business is a popular purpose besides debt and credit card
  • Small business purpose has the highest interest rate among all other purposes
  • Majority of the fully paid borrowers have a lower revolving utilization rate compared with the majority of not fully paid borrowers.
  • Majority of borrowers who use the money for credit card have the higher revolving utilization rate at about 50%. While majority of borrowers who use the money for home improvement have the lowest revolving utilization rate at about 30%.

In conclusion, for numerical variable, we found that:

  • Revolving balance: Not fully paid borrowers that have a revolving balance more than 50k are 29% more than fully paid borrowers
  • Income and FICO distribution do not differ much among the two kinds of borrowers.
  • However, not fully paid borrowers that have met the credit policy are more likely to get lower interest rate with higher FICO. For fully paid borrowers, metting the credit policy or not doesn't make a significant difference on the correlation between interest rate and FICO.
  • Only fully paid borrowers have more than 2 public records and more than 4 times of 30 days past due payment in the last 2 years. They all have lower-than-average FICO score.
  • Among these borrowers, people with debt consolidation and credit card purposes are likely to get a higher interest rate, but having a lower revolving balance tend to lower the interest rate.

Part 5 - Overall Difference between Not Fully Paid and Fully Paid Borrowers¶

From our previous analysis, we can see that interest rate, rovolving balance, credit policy, revolving utilization rate, public record, and delinquent times are some of the most significant difference between fully paid and not fully paid borrowers. Let's take a final look on how all these are differentiated by different groups.

Part 6 - Conclusion¶

  • Generally, not fully paid borrowers receive higher interest rate, tend to have higher revolving balence and revolving utilization rate, more public records and past due 30 days more often.
  • The main purpose of lending.com for borrowers are debt consolidation, credit card, home improvement. A big part of not fully piad borrowers also focus on small business. Small business has the highest interest rate at about 13.8%. Major purchase has the lowest interest rate at about 11.4%
  • Mean of revolving balance is 16,914. There are 29% more not fully paid borrower than fully paid borrower that have a revolving balance more than 50,000.
  • Income and FICO do not differ significantly by different types of borrowers. Both have mean log of annual income at 10.89 and FICO at 698. The higher FICO, the lower the interest rate.
  • Not fully paid borrowers that have met the credit policy are more likely to get lower interest rate with higher FICO. For fully paid borrowers, metting the credit policy or not does not make a significant difference on the correlation between interest rate and FICO.
  • Not fully paid borrowers have more public record and tend not to pay back on time. However, only fully paid borrowers have more than 2 public records and more than 4 counts of 30 days past due payment in the last 2 years. They all have lower-than-average FICO.
  • Among these borrowers, people with debt consolidation and credit card purposes are more likely to get a higher interest rate, but having a lower revolving balance tend to lower the interest rate.

    shrinking=True, tol=0.001, verbose=False)

This time I tried to use the original data, but I weight the classes during the training process. I also standard the data before training. Accuracy is 14.5% higher than random forest, but precision and recall rate is lower.

Last couple of words!¶

  • In the first five part of this project, I performed an comprehensive exploratory data analysis on categorical variables and numerical variables to better understand each of the origianal features and how they might be associated with not fully paid and fully paid borrowers.
  • Next, as most of the features don't differ much between the two groups, I took a final look on 6 features that seems to differ the most between the two types of borrowers according to our previous analysis.

  • And finally, I concluded some insights on the data.

  • In addition, as a value added part, I used random forest and SVC algorithm to try building models for prediction. However, the dataset is very unbalanced so it becomes a little difficult.
